ce:section.ce:para:
Based on the osteogenic property of adenosine and the bone loss prevention manner of aspirin, we propose that fabrication of bioactive CDs from adenosine and aspirin to not only reserve the biofunction of adenosine and aspirin in facilitating osteogenic differentiation, but also provide an effective and safe osteoinduction agent. To investigate the effects of adenosine, aspirin, adenosine plus aspirin, and AACDs on osteogenic differentiation, hBMSCs were treated with these conditions and differentiated in normal medium (NM) or in osteogenic induction medium (OM) for three weeks. Alkaline phosphatase (ALP), a cell surface glycoprotein, is associated with extracellular matrix formation and mineralization during osteogenic differentiation [29]. Therefore, ALP staining and ALP activity assays were performed to compare the osteogenic differentiation activity of hBMSCs after three weeks of differentiation (Fig. 3
                     ). In normal medium, positive staining was observed in adenosine-, adenosine plus aspirin-, and AACD-treated cells, while aspirin showed no difference compared to the control group. In osteogenic induction medium, AACD-treated cells had significantly higher ALP levels than the adenosine plus aspirin-treated cells. Consistently, the elevated levels of ALP activity were higher in the AACD group than in the adenosine plus aspirin group under both NM and OM conditions (Fig. 3b). Bone matrix maturation and mineralization have been considered as the key markers of osteogenic differentiation [30]. Therefore, we determined the efficiency of the mineralization stage by using alizarin red S (ARS) staining to analyze calcium deposition. As shown in Fig. 4
                     a, the increased amount of mineralized matrix in adenosine-, adenosine plus aspirin-, and AACD-treated cells was observed under OM conditions for 21 days, while aspirin alone did not have any influence on the formation of mineralized matrix. Importantly, the addition of AACDs in normal media exhibited a significant increase in the number of nodules compared with the other three groups, while the negative controls did not show any nodule formation. Furthermore, the ARS stain was subsequently diluted and quantified, and similar trend were observed in both NM and OM conditions (Fig. 4b), which were in agreement with the ALP results. These results indicate that AACDs are bioactive and direct the osteogenic differentiation of hBMSCs in the absence of osteoinductive factors, which might be attributed to osteogenic differentiation being directed by adenosine rather than aspirin. Notably, aspirin alone did not show osteogenic differentiation of hBMSCs given its high dose [31]. However, the combination of adenosine and aspirin might preserve multifunctional properties on hBMSCs, including the promoted osteogenic differentiation and the immunomodulatory effect on osteogenesis in vivo. Collectively, these findings demonstrated that AACDs were capable of not only enhancing but also directing osteogenic differentiation of rBMSCs and that AACDs possessed more effective osteogenic differentiation behavior than the mixture of adenosine and aspirin. The benefits of AACDs in osteogenic differentiation could be attributed to that CDs showed higher cellular retention than its homo-precursors [19], so we speculated that the enhanced cellular levels of AACDs might trigger stronger osteogenic differentiation than the combination of adenosine and aspirin.

To understand and elucidate the mechanism involved in the exposure of CDs or small molecules, RT-PCR was carried out to evaluate the mRNA expression of several key markers, including ALP, runt-related transcription factor 2 (RUNX2), bone sialoprotein (BSP), and osteocalcin (OCN), during the osteogenic differentiation of hBMSCs in normal media for 14 days (Fig. 5
                     ). In agreement with the previous ALP results, a significant increase in the ALP mRNA expression level in the AACD group were observed when compared with that in the control group (Fig. 5a). As expected, the osteogenic transcription factor RUNX2 and the mature bone markers OCN and BSP were expressed at the highest levels in AACD-treated cells after 14 days (Fig. 5
                     b–d). Overall, these results reinforce that AACDs could direct osteogenic differentiation in terms of upregulating the expression of osteoblast gene markers. We speculate that the AACDs might act as a trigger to shift their metabolism toward osteogenic differentiation through the regulation of the role of A2bR-mediated ATP metabolism in bone homeostasis [32].

To further determine the biosafety of AACDs, we exposed mice to AACDs or an adenosine and aspirin mixture. After 28 days, the body weight, hematology, blood biochemistry, and organ histopathology of the mice were evaluated. Neither death nor abnormal behavior were observed at the end of the entire experimental period. As shown in Supplementary Fig. S7, no significant changes were observed in the body weight of all treated groups compared with the control group. Hematology parameters (including white blood cells, red blood cells, mean corpuscular volume, hematocrit, mean corpuscular hemoglobin, hemoglobin, mean corpuscular hemoglobin concentration, and platelets) as well as serum biochemistry parameters (including aspartate aminotransferase, alkaline phosphatase, alanine aminotransferase, albumin, serum creatinine, blood urea nitrogen, total cholesterol and total triglycerides) from all groups did not show any remarkable differences (Figs. 6 and 7

                     ). Additionally, histological analysis of tissues from AACD-treated mice and control mice showed no pathological changes in the heart, lung, kidney, liver or spleen (Fig. 8
                     ). Collectively, these results indicated that no abnormal effects on the mice were observed after exposure to AACDs, indicating its good biosafety for further application.
